# Auth – Login
# Smoke tests for POST /auth/login.
#
# Run the happy-path request first to obtain a fresh JWT token, then paste the
# returned access_token (prefixed with "Bearer ") into the @adminToken /
# @userToken variables at the top of the other .http files in this folder.

@baseUrl = http://localhost:8001/api/v1

### 200 – Happy path: valid credentials → returns JWT access token
# Expected: {"access_token": "...", "token_type": "bearer"}
# Copy the returned access_token and paste it as "Bearer <token>" into token
# variables in other .http files before running their authenticated requests.
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "alice@clicknback.com",
  "password": "Str0ng!Pass"
}

### 401 – Sad path: non-existent user
# Email is not registered in the system.
# Expects: 401 with INVALID_CREDENTIALS error code (not 404, to avoid user enumeration).
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "notfound@example.com",
  "password": "irrelevant"
}

### 401 – Sad path: wrong password
# Valid registered email but incorrect password.
# Expects: 401 with INVALID_CREDENTIALS error code (same shape as non-existent user).
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "alice@clicknback.com",
  "password": "wrongpassword"
}

### 422 – Sad path: malformed email format
# Pydantic rejects the payload before the service layer is reached.
# Expects: 422 Unprocessable Entity with a validation detail array.
POST {{baseUrl}}/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "not-an-email",
  "password": "irrelevant"
}
